			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">As someone who is supposed to have aggro and has very few means of getting it:
<br />

<br />
I do not expect to have 100% aggro lock all the time.  Let's face it, mobs get annoyed at stuff.  All I ask if I'm tanking are the following things (the summary is at the end for those with short attention spans):
<br />

<br />
1)  If you're likely to get aggro, stay close to me.  This prevents pong, and lessens the amount of time that you will be hit, since I don't have to run after the thing to get it off you.
<br />

<br />
2)  If you have time and options, DOT's are actually better than nukes for aggro control.  The damage on a DOT, while often more than a nuke by the end, takes time to accumulate.  That means I have time to build aggro along with the DOTs.  On nukes, the damage is all up front and I have to play catchup.  That's ok with me, if it's ok with you... just be aware that a particular amount of DD damage will likely get you hit more than the same amount of DOT damage (obviously stacking for larger values is another story).
<br />

<br />
3)  If you can prevent your aggro through artificial means such as Evade or Jolt, please do so.
<br />

<br />
4)  Warriors LOVE rangers who do more damage with bows than melee.  I can't speak for everyone, but if you're unloading an endless quiver on something and I'm in your LOS, tell me to get my sexy butt out of your way.  I'm happy to oblige.  Likewise, if a rogue needs me to help reposition to give them a BS vantage point, I'm happy to turn the mob around... just remind me in case I didn't notice the lack of space.
<br />

<br />
5)  Warriors hate Root.  It reduces aggro to a matter of simple distance, and unfortunately, amazingly few people practice the use of max melee range.  This does not, however, mean that caster's shouldn't root a mob.  If that's what you need to do to help your situation, then by all means do so.  But please....please....please.... announce loudly and clearly that you have done so.  If I know the mob is rooted I can stand right inside of it and make sure it doesn't turn on anyone else.
<br />

<br />
6)  Do NOT run around if you have aggro.  Unless it's rooted, STAND STILL.  I will not be able to get close enough for long enough to hit and taunt it off you if it's a moving target.  You run, you die... it's that simple.
<br />

<br />
7)  Paladins will inevitably take some aggro off a warrior.  Many warriors will complain about this.  Why?  I have no idea.  A paladin is not a paper tank.  Don't sweat it if they pull some aggro by accident (or even for a reason).  Trust me, a Paladin can take care of themself... they aren't going to roll over and die before the Warrior regains aggro, even if that takes a little bit.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So to sum up:  Stay close for big things like Slow, don't be afraid to DOT, do what you can to minimize your aggro, let me know if you need the thing moved, announce roots, stand still, and don't worry about the Paladin - he knows what he's doing.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Riliana Steelthong<br />_________________<br />Riliana Steelthong
<br />

<br />
